thread.title: Aust stocks end slightly higher

title: Aust stocks end slightly higher
text:
Mon, Sep 14, 2015, 5:28 PM AEST - Australia Markets closed Aust stocks end slightly higher AAP – 17 minutes ago Print 
The Australian share market has ended higher ahead of the US Federal Reserve's decision on interest rates. 
The benchmark S&P/ASX200 index closed up 0.5 per cent but volumes were light as investors shirked from taking large positions. 
"The Fed decision will hold the market to ransom this week. We are likely to tread water for the next four days," said IG market strategist Evan Lucas. 
If the Fed does raise official interest rates, it would be the first such hike since 2008 in the world's biggest economy. 
US stocks ended last week on a high note, while on Monday shares in Hong Kong and Shanghai were up in early trade. However, Tokyo's benchmark index closed 1.6 per cent lower. 
On Monday, local investors largely ignored the political turmoil in Australia, after communications minister Malcolm Turnbull said he would challenge Prime Minister Tony Abbott for the Liberal Party leadership. 
Commonwealth Bank shares lost 58 cents to $74.55 after a shortfall in its equity raising from retail shareholders, although other financial stocks remained positive. Westpac gained 49 cents to $30.99, National Australia Bank rose 35 cents to $30.54, and ANZ added 26 cents to $27.78. 
Macquarie shares added $1.77, or 2.34 per cent, at $77.57 after the investment and banking firm said it expects profit in the half year to September to be 40 per cent higher from a year ago. 
Energy stocks were mixed after the Papua New Guinea-focused Oil Search rejected an $11.6 billion overture from Woodside, saying it grossly undervalued the company. 
Woodside ended flat at $28.41, Oil Search gained four cents to $7.49, while Santos rose five cents to $4.51. 
In the media sector, the Ten Network rose one cent to 17.5 cents on news that the competition watchdog had put the brakes on Foxtel's bid for a 15 per cent stake in the free-to-air broadcaster. 
KEY FACTS 
* At 1630 AEST on Monday, the benchmark S&P/ASX200 index was up 25.4 points, or 0.5 per cent, at 5,096.5 points. 
* The broader All Ordinaries index was up 24.2 points, or 0.47 per cent, at 5,120.5 points. 
* September share price index futures contract was up 23 points at 5,091 points, with 106,816 contracts traded. 
* The price of gold in Sydney at 1700 AEST was $US1,108 per fine ounce, down $US2.20 on Friday's price of $US1,110.20.
